{
  "texts": [
    "In contrast, Algorithm 3.1 incorporates the interaction term directly into the learned velocity field, allowing the propagation step to be performed independently for each particle as in (2.11), with a complexity of O(N).",
    "But in practice, the training phase is often more time-consuming than the propagation phase since the training involves multiple iterations to optimize the neural network parameters, while propagation requires only a single pass through the data.In this sense, Algorithm 3.2 is recommended in practice for challenging problems with a large number of particles.If the initial density p 0 has the analytical expression like the Gaussian distribution, then the initial score function s θ0 (•) is computed by the direct minimization of the following loss due to (3.11):Ω s θ 0 (•) -S[ p0](x, t0) + K * p0(x) 2 p0(x) dx Ω S[ p0](x, t0) -K * p0(x) 2 p0(x) dx ≈ N i=1 s θ 0 (X (i) 0) -S[ p0](X (i) 0, t0) + K * p0(x) 2 N i=1 S[ p0](X (i) 0, t0) -K * p0(x) 2,where S[ p 0] is defined in (2.7).",
    "3.3.Error analysis of Algorithm 3.1.",
    "Now we focus on analyzing the discrete error associated with Algorithm 3.1.",
    "The following theorem demonstrates that the discrete numerical error of Algorithm 3.1 is on the order of 1/ √ N, where N represents the number of particles utilized in the algorithm."
  ]
}